# Part 1 – Introduction to Vulnerability Analysis

## Objective

I want to understand what Vulnerability Analysis is and how to do a vulnerability assessment using Nmaps NSE vulnerability scripts.

---

# What is Vulnerability Analysis?

Vulnerability Analysis is the process of finding security weaknesses in systems, applications and services before they can be exploited by someone.

Unlike Network Scanning, which finds hosts and services Vulnerability Analysis checks if those services have known security weaknesses.

The goal of Vulnerability Analysis is to:

- Find vulnerabilities

- Check security risks

- Decide what to fix first

- Make the security better

---

# Vulnerability Analysis Workflow

1. Find the target

2. Identify what services are running

3. Detect what software versions are used

4. Compare them to known vulnerabilities

5. Write down the findings

---

## 1. Update the Nmap Script Database

### Scenario

I need to refresh the NSE script database before I do a vulnerability assessment.

### Command

```bash

sudo nmap --script-updatedb

```

### Description

This command updates the Nmap script database so it knows about newly installed or updated scripts.

### Screenshot

![Alt text](screenshots/nmap-script-updatedb.png)

---

## 2. Run the Vulnerability Script Category

### Scenario

I want to do a vulnerability assessment against the target.

### Command

```bash

sudo nmap --script 192.168.1.10

```

### Description

This command runs all Nmap NSE scripts in the vuln category to find known vulnerabilities that the target has.

Replace the IP address with the target IP address.

### Screenshot

![Alt text](screenshots/nmap-vuln-scan.png)

---

## 3. Save the Vulnerability Report

### Scenario

I want to save the vulnerability assessment results for documentation.

### Command

```bash

sudo nmap --script 192.168.1.10 -oN vulnerability-scan.txt

```

### Description

This command saves the scan results in a text file so I can look at them later and make a report.

### Screenshot

![Alt text](screenshots/vulnerability-report.png)

---

## 4. Review the Saved Report

### Scenario

I want to look at the generated vulnerability report.

### Command

```bash

vulnerability-scan.txt

```

### Description

This command opens the saved report, in a pager so it is easier to navigate and look at.

### Screenshot

![Alt text](screenshots/review-vulnerability-report.png)

